257. malis: from mella. No suffering attends the actual ful- filment of the prophecy in Book VII. (112-129). On reaching Italy, the Trojans use broad cakes as platters (mensae) for their food, and then eat the platters themselves. Virgil introduces the prophecy because it was one of the traditional stories associated with Aeneas. It serves the artistic purpose, however, of increasing the apprehensions of the Trojans. ’
